<LP>
   BUSH PROPOSED major initiatives for Latin America,
including substantial relief on the nearly $12 billion in the
region's debt held by the U.S. government. The policy also
calls for as much as $300 million in multilateral grants to
foster private investment, and foresees eventually turning
the entire Western Hemisphere into a free-trade zone.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   AT&amp;T predicted a drop in second-quarter earnings because
of lower equipment sales and the costly startup of its bank
credit card. The company's shares sank $2.125 on the news,
and many analysts withdrew recommendations to buy AT&amp;T stock.
   ---
   Democrats offered possible cuts in popular benefit
programs, in a move to reciprocate for Bush's statement that
he is willing to raise taxes.
   ---
   Stocks and bonds rose in further reaction to Bush's
statement on taxes. The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained
19.80 points to close at 2862.13.
   ---
   Japan and the U.S. settled most issues in talks on
structural trade impediments. Negotiators were pushing to
reach a final pact today.
   ---
   Leading economic indicators rose 0.8% in May after a 0.1%
decline in April. The index's second reversal in four months
lends support to the belief that a recession is unlikely, but
some worrisome signals persist.
   ---
   Suspected price-fixing by airlines is the focus of a new
Justice Department inquiry. United, Delta and America West
have been asked for information on their ties to the
industry's clearinghouse on fares.
   ---
   Accounting rule makers agreed to delay by a year, until
1993, the effective date of a regulation requiring companies
to account for the costs of non-pension retirement benefits.
   ---
   Fluor and Parsons won contracts to help overhaul and
expand Saudi petroleum facilities. Analysts valued each job
at as much as $5 billion.
   ---
   Siemens plans to invest more than $600 million in East
Germany in the next few years. Separately, Allianz bought 51%
of the nation's insurance monopoly for $163.1 million.
   ---
   A bill to reregulate cable TV rates and encourage new
competitors to challenge existing cable companies was
approved by a House panel.
   ---
   First Executive picked its ex-auditor to be chief
financial officer in a move designed to tighten internal
controls and to insulate Chairman Fred Carr from outside
contacts.
   ---
   The ties of all failed S&amp;Ls to Drexel and its former
junk-bond chief, Michael Milken, are being investigated by an
FDIC task force.
   ---
   The CFTC criticized sharply the SEC's conclusion that
program selling in futures markets triggered a 6.9%
stock-market drop last October.
   ---
   RJR Nabisco hopes to reset the interest rate on $2.6
billion of its junk bonds at 16 1/2%, a much lower level than
bond specialists estimated before the firm announced its
refinancing.
   ---
   Stiffer prison sentences and fines for safety and health
violations by employers were approved on an 11-5 vote by the
Senate Labor Committee.
   ---
   Laidlaw's founder plans to step down as chief executive in
August and resign as chairman at year end.
